## How to work

Work one policy at a time: inventory the required policies, then reconcile and
verify each in turn. Do not rewrite the whole policy corpus in one
undifferentiated pass. Follow the steps in order.

### 1. INSPECT before writing

INSPECT the project: enumerate its languages, frameworks, package managers,
test frameworks, dependency manifests, and existing CONTRIBUTING / TESTING /
DEVELOPMENT docs. Do not invent commands or tools — every command you declare
must be real.

### 2. COMPLETE each canonical file under {{ canonical_dir }}

**Marker states — the vocabulary you author with**

Every machine-checkable line is exactly one of these states. Pick the one that
matches reality; the validator checks each line's SHAPE, not your intent:

- `RALPH-FACT: <key>: <value>` — a RESOLVED, verified project fact (a command,
  path, name, version — never an adjective or aspiration).
- `RALPH-FACT: <key>: RALPH-PENDING (assumed <date>); review trigger: <cond>` —
  a DEFERRED fact: it applies but cannot be resolved yet. It reaches readiness,
  and a dev cycle resolves it when the trigger fires.
- `RALPH-COMMAND: <approved-tool …>` — a runnable verification gate. The first
  token must be an approved gate tool. The validator does NOT execute it, so a
  correctly-named but not-yet-installed tool is a valid declaration.
- `RALPH-INAPPLICABLE: <reason>` — the gate NEVER applies to this project (for
  example, no graphical surface to test). This is "never", not "not yet".
- `RALPH-PENDING: <approved-tool …> (assumed <date>); review trigger: <cond>` —
  a DEFERRED gate: it applies but is not wired yet (tool not installed, scanner
  not chosen). It reaches readiness, and a dev cycle wires it when the trigger
  fires. Accepted on EVERY policy, including the testing and verification gates.
- `RALPH-REVIEW: <procedure>; evidence: <record>; owner: <role>` — a required
  human/manual review that no command can replace.

The distinction agents most often get wrong is deferral vs never-applies:
"we will have this, just not yet" is ALWAYS `RALPH-PENDING`, never
`RALPH-INAPPLICABLE`. Every `RALPH-PENDING` needs a real intended tool (gate
form), an `(assumed <YYYY-MM-DD>)` stamp with a real date, and a concrete
`review trigger:`; it is a debt a future dev cycle must repay.

**Facts and schema**

- When a finding reports an older policy schema, the interactive CLI has
  already offered upgrade or freeze. On the upgrade path, reconcile the newer
  bundled contract into the customized file while preserving verified facts and
  stricter project rules. Never replace a customized file wholesale.
- Replace every `RALPH-FACT:` line with a verified project fact.

**Gate commands**

- Add at least one runnable `RALPH-COMMAND:` line for each verification gate
  (testing, typecheck, lint, dependency audit, verification), or an explicit
  `RALPH-INAPPLICABLE:` line with a reason (the gate never applies), or a
  `RALPH-PENDING:` deferral (the gate applies but is not wired yet — see
  step 4).
- Every `RALPH-COMMAND:` value MUST start with an approved gate tool: the
  validator checks the FIRST whitespace-separated token against a fixed
  allowlist and rejects everything else. Approved tools: {{ approved_tools }}.
  Wrap any other tool in an approved runner (e.g. `make <target>`,
  `uv run <tool>`, `npx <tool>`).
- Use `RALPH-REVIEW: <procedure>; evidence: <record>; owner: <role>` for
  required human/manual review. Never invent a shell command or claim manual
  evidence that was not performed; report unavailable review as a blocker.
- For typecheck and lint policies, declare every applicable language via
  `RALPH-LANG: <Language>` followed by a RALPH-COMMAND, RALPH-INAPPLICABLE, or
  RALPH-PENDING line.

**Placeholders and citations**

- Sections marked with a `REPLACE-ME` comment carry their own in-place
  instructions: follow the instruction, then delete the comment. `REPLACE-ME`
  is a validator placeholder, so readiness stays blocked while any such comment
  remains.
- Add the citation block under `## Research basis` with publisher, title, URL
  (http), and review date.

**Applicability — track, don't drop**

- For an inactive conditional domain, record the dated inactive decision and
  reactivation trigger in the applicability override. Then either remove an
  uncustomized seeded policy file, or retain a customized policy as an inactive
  historical record without deleting verified content. Within a required
  policy, remove only optional clauses proven inapplicable; never leave an
  empty required heading or mark an applicable requirement complete without
  evidence.
- When deterministic signals are incomplete, record an explicit decision in
  `{{ applicability_overrides_path }}` under `[domains]` as either
  `domain = "required; reason: ...; review trigger: ..."` or
  `domain = "inactive; reason: ...; review trigger: ..."`. Never use an
  override to evade an applicable mandatory policy.

**Finish clean**

- Where an existing project rule is STRICTER than the starter text, preserve
  the stricter rule — reconcile contradictions by adapting the stricter side,
  never by weakening the policy.
- Delete the `RALPH-STARTER-TEMPLATE` banner comment once the file holds
  verified project policy; readiness stays blocked while the banner remains.
- The finished file must read as durable policy: every sentence tells a future
  agent how to FOLLOW or ENFORCE the policy. Do not leave fill-in instructions,
  references to starters or placeholders, or validator mechanics in the prose.
  Keep machine markers confined to the file's one designated marker section (a
  required heading), and keep that section minimal.

### 3. MIGRATE existing policy-like content

Move existing project policy-like content into the matching canonical file and
add `{{ migrated_marker }}` at the old location (replacing `<canonical-filename>`
with the destination), OR remove the recognized heading so the file is no
longer a candidate. For standard community files (SECURITY.md, CONTRIBUTING.md,
and similar ecosystem-convention locations) KEEP the file and its heading and
use the migrated marker — their location and headings are conventions other
tools and humans rely on.

### 4. WIRE each gate — confirm it exists, do not repair it

Wire each declared gate so its command resolves to the real check (for example
a `make` target that invokes the actual tool), and confirm the command EXISTS.
You MAY run it once to confirm it resolves; you do NOT fix failing checks or
make a red gate green. Document any command that cannot be run and the reason.

If a gate or fact genuinely cannot be resolved yet — the tool is not installed,
the scanner is not chosen, the fact is too young — do NOT build it now and do
NOT leave a bare `TODO` (readiness treats `TODO` as an unresolved placeholder
and blocks on it). Record it as a **deferral** with `RALPH-PENDING`, the
first-class "applies but not resolvable yet" state. It reaches readiness (a new
project is never blocked on it) and is resolved by ordinary dev-cycle agents
when its trigger fires — never by re-running this remediation. Every
`RALPH-PENDING` line carries an `(assumed <YYYY-MM-DD>)` stamp with a real date
and a `review trigger: <condition>` clause:

- Gate form (may replace a `RALPH-COMMAND` / `RALPH-INAPPLICABLE`, including
  inside a `RALPH-LANG:` block). The first token MUST be an approved gate tool
  so the eventual gate is real:
  `RALPH-PENDING: pytest (assumed 2026-07-12); review trigger: once test deps are installed`
- Fact form (the `RALPH-PENDING` sentinel leads the fact value):
  `RALPH-FACT: secret_scan_command: RALPH-PENDING (assumed 2026-07-12); review trigger: once a scanner is chosen`

`RALPH-PENDING` is accepted on EVERY policy, including the testing and
verification gates — a new project whose test runner is not installed may defer
it (`RALPH-PENDING: pytest (assumed 2026-07-12); review trigger: once test deps
are installed`), trusting a dev-cycle agent to wire it when the trigger fires.
Prefer a real `RALPH-COMMAND` when the gate can be declared now (the validator
never executes it, so an uninstalled-but-named tool is fine), and reserve
`RALPH-INAPPLICABLE` for a gate that genuinely NEVER applies (not merely
"not yet"). Every RALPH-PENDING you write is a debt a future dev cycle must
repay, so name the real intended tool and a concrete review trigger.

